f:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SUI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI's status as a high-performance Layer 1 blockchain creates funding rate volatility driven by ecosystem announcements, developer activity, and institutional adoption cycles. The token's moderate trading volume on MEXC provides arbitrage opportunities without excessive slippage, while the exchange's aggressive listing strategy ensures early access to SUI derivatives trading."}]]}]
10:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI/USDT funding rates on MEXC have shown correlation with major blockchain milestones and DeFi protocol launches on the SUI network. During ecosystem growth phases, positive funding rates often exceed 0.1% per 8-hour period as leveraged long positions dominate. Network upgrade announcements and partnership reveals typically trigger 24-48 hour periods of elevated funding rates. The token's relatively recent market presence means historical data spans shorter timeframes compared to established Layer 1s, creating less predictable seasonal patterns."}]]}]
11:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategy"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure enables profitable funding arbitrage on SUI/USDT with smaller rate differentials compared to traditional exchanges. Traders can capitalize on the 8-hour funding cycle by establishing opposing positions across venues when rate differentials exceed 0.02-0.03%. The exchange's aggressive listing approach often results in SUI perpetual availability before major competitors, creating temporary arbitrage windows. Cross-exchange funding rate spreads for SUI frequently widen during Asian trading hours due to MEXC's regional user base concentration."}]]}]
12:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Market Dynamics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI's position as a newer Layer 1 blockchain introduces smart contract risk and ecosystem dependency that can trigger rapid funding rate changes. MEXC's thinner order books for SUI/USDT compared to tier-1 exchanges may result in increased slippage during volatile periods, affecting arbitrage execution. The exchange's questionable volume reporting practices require careful verification of actual liquidity before executing large funding arbitrage positions. Regulatory uncertainty around MEXC's operations adds counterparty risk that traders must factor into longer-term funding rate strategies."}]]}]
13:["$","$L15",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes SUI funding rates on MEXC different from other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's zero maker fees eliminate trading costs for funding arbitrage strategies, while their aggressive listing approach often provides earlier access to SUI perpetuals. The 8-hour funding cycle and ±0.375% rate caps create distinct arbitrage windows compared to exchanges with different parameters."},{"question":"How volatile are SUI/USDT funding rates during ecosystem events?","answer":"SUI funding rates can spike to maximum caps during major ecosystem announcements, network upgrades, or significant DeFi protocol launches. These events often trigger 24-48 hour periods where funding rates exceed 0.1% per cycle as speculative positions increase."},{"question":"What are the main risks of SUI funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"Key risks include MEXC's thinner liquidity creating slippage, regulatory uncertainty around the exchange, and SUI's ecosystem dependency causing rapid rate changes. The exchange's volume reporting practices also require verification of actual market depth before position sizing."},{"question":"When are SUI funding rates typically highest on MEXC?","answer":"SUI funding rates often peak during Asian trading hours due to MEXC's user base concentration, and around major blockchain milestones or partnership announcements. The 8-hour UTC cycle times (00:00, 08:00, 16:00) align with different regional trading sessions, creating predictable volume patterns."}]}]
